Our club has 25 members, and wishes to pick a president, secretary, and treasurer.  In how many ways can we choose the officers, if individual members may hold more than one office?
inference:
There are 25 ways to choose the president.  After the president is chosen, there are 24 ways to choose the secretary.  After the president and secretary are chosen, there are 23 ways to choose the treasurer.  Therefore, there are $25\times 24\times 23 = 13,800$ ways to choose the officers.
Final Answer: $\boxed{13,800}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: There are 25 choices for each position, so there are $25\times 25\times 25=\boxed{15,\!625}$ ways that the positions can be filled.
